\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid8863920 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Your name and address please?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 John Morrison. 28, Portrona Drive, Stornoway, Isle of Lewis.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Could you tell me the year of your marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 1945.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 And your year of birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 1905.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 And your birthplace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Barras. Isle of Lewis.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Could you tell me how many years you lived in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 I - well I came to school in Stornoway at fourteen. A}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3871911\charrsid16660515 
nd I was for six years in the Ni}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 cholson Institute, so I was - back and forward weekends and lived at home at holidays of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 But it was the same family home that you had right through the period?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Your family didn't move house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 I had four brothers and three sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Could you give me an idea of the family order and roughly the years between?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 W
ell I was the eldest. And a sister born in 1907. Another born in 1908. They were both twins and the twin boys were born with them both died in infancy. My next brother was born 1910, another brother in 1912. Another one in 1914. A sister at 1916 and my yo
ungest brother 1923.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Do you know how old your father was when you were born?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 When I was born he would be - thirty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 He came from Braga, Isle of Lewis.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 And his occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 He was a shopkeeper to begin 
with. He had worked in Glasgow in his young days, to come back to Barras, where incidentally he had been brought up with friends, not with relatives. This was - I think - an offshoot of an old custom, where children sometimes when they were weaned lived w
ith grandparents. But he lived with cousins in Barras, and - he stayed on in Barras. Set up business in a small shop, and - then eventually married, settled down in the village and that's been - our home all the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 When he settled down in the village did he open a shop - again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Oh - well he started his shop - in the early 1900's and continued - business 'til Carmichael, one of my brother's was still running it. Yes, in conjunction with the Post Office now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Your brother was mentioning something about him being a Registrar of births?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Well, he came Registrar of births in 1908, and - again - he became - Inspector of Poor which was tantamount to the - Poor Relief, your - of - you know, your Public Assistance Officer - around 1916 I think. 
And - sub-collector of rates for the parish council in those days of course. Then - he continued with that every - there were changes now in 1929 Local Government Act which - put poor law under - the county councils, and then he became Assistant Public As
s
istance Officer of the district. Officer was in Stornoway and he was one of three rural assistants he had you see, and he continued in these posts 'til 1946 I think, he had to retire then, he was over the age, over sixty-five, and - all the men re - had t
o retire because of some of the young men coming back from war you see, and - he continued as Registrar - oh - up 'til - '59 or so, he - he was fifty-one years a Registrar. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 When he was the Poor Relieving Officer did he have much direct contact with the people who were applying?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh very much. Very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Was it up to him to decide the merits of the case and the amount of relief?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Well - well of course he was the administrative officer for the parish council. And he had to investigate 
any applications and then submit them to the parish council, and the parish council had to actually decided the amount of relief. And then it was his job to see that they got paid - that amount you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Do you remember your father ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
No. No. You see, he had quite a croft - oh I would say shortly before the first world war, and he was a very strong active man and he took a great interest in his croft, so - he had the shop and he had all these local government posts and - the 
croft was more of a - a - a hobby really, but he - he just seemed to relish - doing all these things and he was a big powerful man and - I think quite good at his job, the other jobs as well. He just seemed to enjoy his life very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 He had a lot of energy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Very energetic man, yes, very energetic. And in those days of course - he had to cycle, and he cycled from Shawbost to Ness, to do his visiting here. He had to visit everybody who was getting relief - twice a year, this was a statutory requi
rement, and of course - he had to visit new cases - as they cropped up. And then of course in the wintertime - he had to collect the rates. But he - usually he went round schools, he - he had a - arranged - had arranged to be at a school on a certain day 
o
r a certain time and then people in the village - was for - their convenience of course. And he would collect the rates and then he had to account for that to the clerk, the clerk to the council was the man in Stornoway. Aye, he became the clerk to the po
o
r parish council, there were a parish council in each parish and one man was - became the clerk to the poor councils eventually, and of course he was the - he was a very excellent man in his way, and he had - much wider experience of the rural - these rur
al collects, so he kept them right on the legal side of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did he talk much to you about the conditions of people at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Well - one became aware of the conditions, you mean you could see from the births you - and then you - heard inci
dentally about - the odd case in some other part of the island, of the parish perhaps. Oh yes. I - took an interest in this and indeed this is - clearly what led to my coming into local government later on, it wasn't - pre-determined, however that's the w
ay it happened, we'll come to that perhaps later on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Was your mother - how old was she when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Now, she would be probably twenty - five I think. Twenty-five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Where did she come from?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 She came from Back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Whereabouts is that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 This is in the parish of Stornoway, it's down - it's - between - halfway between - Stornoway and Torsta, North Torsta.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Had she any jobs before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Well, she used to be in domestic service in her young days, and - just befor
e her marriage she was housekeeper to my uncle, who was the Minister on Barras - at that time, he was the - Church of Free - United Free Church minister on Barras, and she went with him - at that time he hadn't married, but he married shortly afterwards. 
And - then she married shortly after that again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Your uncle on her side or your uncle on your father's side?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh, her own brother, her own brother, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 After she married did she ever take paid work again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Can you describe to me your house where you spent your childhood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Yes, it was a large house by - standards in those days, was quite a good house - it had been built on the site of an old - school house actually, there's been an old }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3871911\charrsid16660515 G}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 aelic school house, and - it ha
d belonged to I think eventually it reverted to the estate, and then - somebody in the village bought it and then - needed some money and is old - the old - ruin my father and he built - a - quite a biggish house in those days, and - it consisted of - the
 
usual type of - Lewis house in those days where you had - three - well there were three rooms downstairs, three rooms upstairs you see, and then there was an - another lower one attached where we had - one room and a back kitchen. And at one time the room
 there was used as a - an offshoot of the shop you see, this was for the convenience of our neighbours because the shop was about three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3871911\charrsid16660515  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 quarters of a mile away from the house. But our own neighbours - you - there was a little shop in the house as well you see. Supplemented the other one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 The three rooms downstairs, was one a kitchen, one a living room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
The kitchen was in the back of the lower part, the - the back - yes, and then you came through - from the bigger house - there was a - there was a 
stairs in the lower end too, and - of course there were quite a large family of us - and we used to have a maid - when - the children came. And - sometimes we had a carter who lived in - you know, the - the transport of goods for the shop - was by - horse
 and cart, and - we used to have a - a - a man around - a general handy man who - who would come to Stornaway with the cart, take over what was required at the shop and help - help generally around the place.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Doing work outside?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Doing work outsi
de, the outside work that had to be done sometimes, like if you're hiring a - a - a neighbour by the day, just to come in to Stornoway and sometimes my father would come - sometimes on occasion he had somebody helping in the shop. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did this carter sleep inside the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Yes, some of them did, lived in the house with us, yes. - Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Sharing the room with the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh could be, this is just a wee bit - way back, but possibly. Possibly. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 And the maid you had, did she also sleep in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Yes, she slept in, yes. But they lived very much as member of the family. Yes. And they became kind of - personal friends for ever after you know, yes, some of them. Well, one of them - I was very friendly with, this would be one of the l
ast ones' before the first world war, we - of course after the war was no occasion for them, but - I became very friendly with this - man, and he came back from the war and he - he - he started work as a taxi driver and then he acquired a bus in the year 
1
9 - early 192o's, and he taught me to drive on his model Ford T bus, when I was very young, I was at - pupil at the Nicholson Institute, and - we were very good friends always until he died a year ago. Yes - and - some of the others, you always had a kind
 of - personal regard for them, even some of them you remembered very dimly. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Would the maid call you by your first name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh yes, by your Christ - first name.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Never master or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh - oh - oh nothing - oh no, no,, t
hey were all - they were somebody from the village or somebody from the next village, and they were really - almost - neighbours coming in to help you out except that they got some kind of - salary, even though it was very small in those days. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did they eat their meals with you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Mm hm. Oh yes, oh yes, oh there was no - there was no - there was no class distinction, we sprang from the same roots and there was none of these distinctions like that at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Can you tell me, did you ever have any other relatives or any lodgers living in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Yes, for a time - we - you see there was trouble in the churches, the reunion took place in 1900 where the Free Church and the United Free church was - formed you see, and - my uncle - who was
 in - well he - he became the minister in 1903, I - really the trouble was over by then, but he opted to go into the United Free church, and - there were a great deal of - legal trouble between the Free church and the United Free church about the properti
e
s, who was going to get the church, who was going to get the Manse, and - it went on for several years, and I think about - 1907 - the thing may possibly have settled in the House of Lords eventually and the Free Church won the - the case you see. Now he 
had to leave the Manse, and my parents made - part of the house available to him. And he and his wife and their maid lived there - for several years, until a new Manse and a new church were erected for him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 This was while there were still several young children at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Yes, we would have been quite small - and I was in end out you know, and my - my uncle's wife was from Edinburgh you know, gaelic and I was - bi-lingual at quite an early age. Yes. And evidently - I - I used to hear my mother telli
ng me about an elderly neighbour who used to come in, and when he came in I evidently spoke to him in English and when the old lady came in I spoke to them in gaelic, and he thought this was a - a great pointer to intelligence then. I realized at that age
 that he was more intelligent than the old ladies. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 What was generally the language your parents spoke to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh agelic. Gaelic, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did you learn your English at school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Well - I learnt a - a good deal in the masne - next d
oor you see, with my aunt and my uncle of course had to use English because she was - English speaking and - later had to use English as well to communicate - so that I had I would have had to have been quite fluent in English before I went to school. Yes
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 In your home who did the washing, was that the maid or your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Oh it probably a co-operative effort I would imagine, of course eventually there would have been a - quite a lot of it. Yes. Oh the maid would - do, I expect, a good deal of it
 but - my mother was always very busy. Oh she was very fine cook and - all that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did she do the cooking aided by the maid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes, she was the cook, she was - excellent, excellent baker. Yes, you find this with a lot of Lewis pe
ople, yes, splendid bakers. But she had - she'd had a - a good deal of experience, she had worked in - fairly well to do places I think in - on the mainland, Glasgow, Aberdeen and that kind of thing, so - she had quite a good knowledge, a very intelligent
 
person and - she could - pick up things very quickly. Yes, and even - when - quite - when she was still quite a mature - person I remember some lady - coming to the school I think and - teaching - girls how to make - an improved type of barley cake, this 
-
 this we would have thought was - a terrible thing for any other lady from outside Lewis to come and teach Lewis women to make - barley - bread, but this lady had some and she used it and - and she - quite agreed that it was quite a big improvement, yes. 
I think it was a case of using some fats and - and sugar which they evidently hadn't used before, they used to get - a rather hard thin bannock, but this very much richer thing and - and it was very very tasty as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did your mother make things from oats, I've read that oats were very widely used for baking on Lewis?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oat cake, oh yes, oat cake, barley bread, see her flour scones of course and cakes and she was very good at cakes as well, you know, yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Could you tell me something about the family's clothing, how you were supplied with clothes, whether they were made at home or bought?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Yes, she did - we had a sewing mach - one of the Singer - very early models of the Singer sewing machines, a - a treadle model I remember, it must have c
ome into the house about - 1908, and - again she was very skilfull at that and - and then I had another uncle on - on my father's side who stayed with us after the 1920's, he had had a rather rough time during the war, he had touch - contracted rheumatic 
f
ever and his heart was dickey, and he had been a mason to trade but - one of these people who could turn his hand to anything. I remember he used to - even after I came to school here in the Nicholson I still used to wear trousers that my uncle Norman mad
e for me. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 How did you get the cloth, did you buy it from people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Well - occasionally my mother made a web of - Harris tweed, those days of course it wasn't what it is today. People got the wool, we got it spun and - then dyed - dyed the
 wool first then got it spun and then they would have to go and find a weaver, there was no weaver in our own village, we had to go to Shawbust to get it done. And then - my father had contacts through the shop of course with firms on the mainland and the
 travelers used to come round and - sometimes they would sell a web of tweed to - some contacts of these - firms it may be. Yes. Oh she - she - she had a wide range of interests. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did she knit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh yes. She knitted too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Do you remember her buying any clothes readymade, knitted things or trousers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Oh yes, oh we bought - yes, of course we had a shop you see and the shopkeepers were all mates in those days from the needle to an anchor but - yes, we - we - we were a general shop and - a
nd drapery and boots and shoes and - the travellers in those days came round from - I remember people who - commercial travelers from firms that came round for thirty years. Yes, men - and they often - we became great personal friends you see, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 What about boots and shoes, how were those obtained?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh they were bought through the - they were bought through the shop, yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did you wear boots all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 No, no. No, once the summer came - you cast your boots aside and you went barefoot. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Can you remember whether new clothes were obtained for any particular festivals or seasons of the year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Mm - no, I suppose just like today that - probably there would be a new garment when you went back to school, that kind of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Not for Easter time though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Oh no, oh well of course Easter never played the same part here as it does in England or anywhere. No, no. Oh no, there was nothing like that. On occasion - there might have been an occasion but - one had a - I r
emember I had a - possibly a Sunday suit, I don't suppose many of us had Sunday suits at - at that age, and occasionally - we - well we went to Sunday school, there were a - sometimes we went to Sunday school in my uncle's church which was over a mile awa
y
, but we weren't all that fussy, we went to the church which was up the road, the Church of Scotland, established church, the established Church of Scotland - with a small congregation but the minister held a Sunday school and we went there because it jus
t -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Because it was near?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Yes, and - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did your parents attend there too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Well, my parents - my parents attended my uncle's church and - occasionally I went to the services along with my father you see. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Can you remember about shoes, how they were repaired, did your father repair shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Yes, indeed, oh yes. Oh yes. Well there was a - there was a - a shoemaker down the road who did - helped occasionally but - mostly we - he did it - himself, he did them himself, a quest
ion of - replacing - a half sole you see when you're - your - your sole wore out of course there was no rubber sole in those days, and he got some huge sheets of leather, a whole hide you see in the shop, and you had to cut it, somebody else'd come in and
 
you buy - you bought what you required, and then heels had to be renewed very often. Normally we wore - pretty heavy shoes with - iron tacks and - very - heel plates. And it was more a case of replacing the heel plates and - and the great thing I had a gr
e
at interest in the - when you - when you developed hole on the - on the upper you see, the patching up there, and - and watching the shoemaker doing this and we were all very interested, the boys - quite interested in doing a neat patch, I was never very 
dexterous at it but - I remember it was one of these things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 At a certain age you were expected to repair your own were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Well - oh well, probably, yes - I've no doubt - that - maybe by the time I became a teenager I was able to do a little bi
t of a job, a wee bit ham}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3871911\charrsid16660515 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 handed but still serviceable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 What about the repairing of clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh well - mother - did this. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 What about the two sisters, the ones that came after you, did they do any mending?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh yes, yes, they were both quite good, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Do you remember your father or any of the boys doing any mending or sewing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 No. No. Oh just wasn't - wasn't done. It wasn't done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 What about other work of the household, cleaning, cooking, washing up, making the fires. 
Do you remember your father doing anything of that kind indoors?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
No, apart from - possibly setting the fire, he was up and - you know, probably - very early, but - when he was up first and that of course he would have to make - make up the fire but 
- more generally it was the maid was - when we had a maid I would imagine who was up first, and - she would probably start the - fire. And then - my mother - my father occasionally - later on of course - later life my - my father probably was - more likel
y
 to be up - fairly earlier. He had to - well - from my early - '30's would it be. He - the - my - this other uncle came into the house, his brother came into us, he became the sub-postmaster and he used - my father's shop as the sub-post office you see, a
nd he wasn't a very robust man so my father - did the early part, he - he went down for the - he had to be down there at eight o'clock every morning you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Can you remember him ever doing anything for you in the way of putting you to bed or wash
ing you or bathing you when you were a small boy, too small to do those things for yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Well - no, I can't remember that, it probably happened but - I can't remember that was ever done on any scale, it would be the womenfolk would be - my mother probably - and having help, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 What about things like telling you stories or reading to you, talking to you about interesting things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Yes, he - he was - he was quite a keen a reader himself, oh yes. And he had - of course you became awar
e that there was people moving in and out or the neighbours coming visiting at night and here you see - the word cailey you see, it promotes something - a typical entertainment, but to us this wasn't it, you went visiting your neighbour's house and you we
n
t caileying you see, this was it, and we had a very very interesting neighbour - a man who - who - he was known as Barras Bard, he was a blacksmith by trade and lived next door. And every night in life he was in our house, and he had - an unlimited store 
of stories, whether they was true or - not. But he had a wonderful imagination, a - a man that was - well - uneducated by modern standards, but - a wonderful gift - of describing - the - nature and natural things and - some - portions of excellent }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3871911\charrsid16660515 G}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 aelic po
etry. And a very intelligent man, and - could understand what was going on in the world outside and that, and - that man was - whoever else who was there he was there. And he died in 1916.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did anybody record the stories and things do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Well a book of his - some of his stories but a lot of it was lost and that, but - there was a schoolmaster in - in the place, and - he - managed to collect - some of the work and - then it was - turned out as a book, but it's out of print long ago. I thin
k I have a copy somewhere around.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 When he came round were you allowed to stay up and listen to these stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Well I would have been allowed more than the rest - I was older you see, and - I - I would have - been there listening to him because -
 they were a never ending sort of wonder, and then - one of my - earliest activities I should imagine, possibly before I again went to school was to go into the smithy, you see, and - trying to reach the - handle for the bellows, this was a great thing yo
u know. Blowing the bellows and watching the fire blaze up and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 He let you do that did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Oh yes. Oh - sometimes, and I - I - I must have been very very small because - remember reaching for this and just almost being lifted off - off the groun
d with it, and the - and there were horses of course from all over came in large numbers, and - it was a great source of interest and - at the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 When he came round what would the procedure be, would he come round sort of after teatime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh he
'd come round late in the evening, yes. Oh probably more eight o'clock, nine o' - in the wintertime, you know, it was dark, he might come in - some - sometime around eight - seven or eight I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 And how late would you sit up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh well now, I - I couldn't remember, probably weren't - I would have to go away by ten o'clock, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Would he stay on later?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh yes, yes, they - they - it depended you see, occasionally we had - we had visitors, well I had an uncle - another 
uncle who was a mason, and - an uncle of my father's who was a mason and I remember he stayed with us for a while while they were building houses in the locality. And of course they were - strangers in a way - they - they weren't strangers exactly, knew -
 
they were acquainted with the bard and with my people, but - this continuing fund of interesting stories, they could never get over them - and - they were - they went out very early these men those days, and they were - my - uncle always say, I'm not goin
g to listen to the - the black}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3871911\charrsid16660515 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 mith's lies tonight. But he would still be there - he - he wouldn't miss anything. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Would people just walk into the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh yes. Knock and then they'd walk straight in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 The door wasn't kept shut?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Do you remember your father ever taking you out without your mother anywhere, just you or perhaps you and a brother or sister or two on any outing anywhere or an excursion?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Not - I don't think so, I think if we ever went anywhere spec
ial - it would be to some function like a - a wedding, I remember - the two of them - taking my - next older brother and myself to a wedding at Back when there was a cousin getting married down at Back, one of my - from - one of my mother's people really,
 
and - we didn't have a - I don't think we had a - horse at the time ourselves, but we were able to get a horse from the farm, there was a farm, small farm next to us, we were able to borrow a horse there and he borrowed my uncle's gig from the manse you s
e
e, and we went over there. Well that was - that would have been during the year of 1916 during the first world war, and I remember went away in the - away - all night, went away in the afternoon probably. Went to this wedding and - spent the night at Back
 and then went Back for one day, back home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did the wedding go on late at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Oh all night, all night, oh yes, yes. Yes, I remember I was very sleepy when I went home. And - my brother was much younger than myself. But - must have been in the 
spring time. I remember my mother coming up in the - early afternoon with a cup of tea and wakening me up and I was - howling my head off you know I was tired - just exhausted. But he was going to start ploughing you see, and he needed somebody to lead th
e horse for the first furrow. So I was - I was the only one available. I remember I - felt miserable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Were weddings occasions where the children were quite accepted, quite young children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Mostly, yes, they - usually there were a special - of cour
se, in those days, the - most of the houses were the old black houses and they were quite roomy - and the - what was really the bed chamber - was turned into a dining room for the occasion, there was long tables all the length of the room. But - usually t
here was a special table set in the barn for the children. And - they had their - feed in there. But - oh most weddings the - the children were provided for. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Do you ever remember your mother going out and leaving your father in charge of you or the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Oh he must have done occasionally, I can't remember any particular - incident, but there would be times no doubt when he did because - I remember the time of the - the big flu epidemic you know, just - at the end of the first war, and - t
here had been very serious cases there and mother and a neighbour, there was one particular case where a mother and - her little - her youngest daughter had died within two days of each other, and - and the - a - a son of the family had died in Glasgow ju
s
t a few weeks earlier, and the father hadn't come back from the funeral, and - I remember that my mother and this other lady next door that - turned to and - done what was needed to try and - ease the situation and - other cases like that I know, she was 
- she was very resourceful like that and very likely to help. So there must have been occasions when he was - mind you by that time I would say that I would have been partly in charge myself you see. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 You were left sometimes in charge of younger children were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh probably. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Were the older two girls, your sisters, given more of that though do you think than the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Well, you see - mother didn't go out an awful lot. No, the - the mothers didn't leave home - very much. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 I suppose your maid would have been in most of the time would she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Well, when we had a maid, oh yes, she - she would - she would perhaps - probably be able to get home occasionally but - most of the time she would be in, it was just one of her roles. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Can you remember any particular jobs you had to carry out regularly at home to help with the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Yes, and we - we - we didn't have a croft, I mentioned before, we didn't have a croft to begin with, but - just before the war, we - we 
- we - got a croft and I think we - we got a cow actually before we got a croft and we were allowed to graze it - on the local - farm, part of the church glebe, and - we all learned to milk - we had of course to see the cow onto the pasture. Go and collec
t it at milking time. And - during the winter as it was housed in a byre, once I became able to clean the byre this was one job I had to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Was that regular?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh this would have been done - daily or - oh yes, quite frequently, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Was that usually done, byres to be cleaned so frequently at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Well ours you see, it wasn't - with the old black house of course the - the - the byres weren't cleaned at all except once a year - well - nearly - once a year mostly, the - the - the
y just tidied up the straw and the manure built up, and then they opened the big door at the back end at the far end of the house and - the cart could back right in and the whole place was cleared out - completely. But - the kind of byre we had then, that
 would have been a small shed at the back of the house and it just had to be done you see, yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Can you remember any other jobs that people had to do in the home, the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh the children had to get the peats in. And I had to get - go 
for water to the well. And sometimes in the dry spell in the - in the middle of the summer, at this time of the year, they had to go quite long distances to get the good drinking water. And even for - washing up purposes we had to go to a burn, which the 
distance I'm sure was - between a quarter of a mile and half a mile away. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did boys and girls do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Boys and girls, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 And they both carried peat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Can you remember any jobs that were considered particula
rly your brothers and your jobs and some that were the girls? Or was there not a demarcation there really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 I wouldn't think so. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Except for the mending?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Mm. Oh yes, oh that kind of thing - little jobs, purely domestic ones - which were 
- you know. Ooh no, I think as far as the - peats and they all helped when they were particularly - you know they were gathering the peats, lifting the peats, and - getting them home and that kind of thing. And then of course when I grew up we had a horse
 
we used to take the peats home. It was quite near us, we could get to the peats in about five minutes walking and we could get a lot home in a day. Yes, sometimes we - if we had our own horse we took ours home ourselves and when we didn't have a horse the
n you had to get two or three of the neighbours to work the same day, bring them all home in one day. So we had a busy day at the peats, and a picnic of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did the children help with cutting the peats?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 No. No. Oh no, when - then we - we got 
- neighbours, we got people from the village to help. My father of course was - was tied down with his own work and he - he - he paid them whatever the - rate was - possibly there were one or two who wouldn't accept anything do you see, but mostly he woul
d pay them whatever the rate was, be a few bob a day probably, and we would have quite a crowd on a big day. A lot of - food to be prepared and there could be as many as a dozen men.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 That was a man's job was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Yes. In the early days, in pre-wa
r - pre 1914 - in our end of the village - the entire male - peater. But in the other - in the other village, and possibly through necessity - it was quite commonplace, I remember quite a way back for the women to cut the peats, well they were widows, the
y
 had nobody else, they would have young families, they had to go out and cut the peats with their neighbours and they - they worked in groups you see. And they went to cut each other's peats and there was no money - transaction at all. But of course each 
- group had to be - fed. As best they could.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 They took food for the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Well, depending on how far away they were, our people - our crowd could come home because they were fairly near, but others had to go anywhere you know, but - a mile or more
 - and - if it was a lot of loss of time then they would take the food out and have a meal out on the moors and then they'd have - they'd have breakfast in the house before they went, they'd have a meal on the moor and possibly - a meal when they came bac
k. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Would you go with them to watch the peat cutting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 It was quite an event was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh yes, quite a day of course and sometimes of course cut it when we were at school, we weren't able to go but then you would go ou
t after school - see them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 What about things like painting and decorating or repairs to your house, improvements to the house, who carried those out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Ah, the painting decorating we did ourselves - my father's and - mother between them. Father wo
uld do any painting and - any - small joiner repairs anything like that he would do himself, and if he needed a tradesman or - we had - relatives who were tradesmen and - probably get one of them - do anything bigger than that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 The small jobs though he did himself?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh he would - oh he would tackle a - quite a few things himself, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
When you were a small boy before you went to school, only about eight or nine, what time did you have to go to bed, do you remember, or was there not a fixed bedtime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 I - I couldn't say definitely, but I should imagine - I think ten o'clock, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
When you were younger than that, about five or six, were you put to bed, was there a sort of bed time ritual if you know what I mean or were you just told to go to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 No, I couldn't - can't remember that far back but - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did you share a bed with your brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did you have the box beds in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 We had one I think on a - at the top of a staircase, I remember 
there were one built in - there, yes. But - mostly they were iron bedsteads.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Your house didn't have a bathroom did it, how did they manage for bathing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh no, just had the bath from - in the kitchen. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Was that on a regular occasion or just when they felt you needed one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh there would be - there would be a - a regular ritual.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 About how often would that be when you were a small boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh probably would be a big bath every week you know, yes, yes, be a good wash anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 You were saying your mother was an accomplished cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 What was usual for breakfast in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh porridge. Porridge and milk. Ah, the usual - staple diet.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Was that all the year round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh as far as possible, of course
 it wasn't possible with one cow, but we had - the first cow we had I remember she was elderly but she was a very very heavy milker, and she also retained her milk for quite a long time, she was - the period she was dry between - in - in calving was - com
p
aratively shore, compared with some of the neighbours who had the small - cattle and a lot of them went dry - oh perhaps three month before they were due to calve, they would be without even some of them may - might have had two cows, and they would still
 be dry, but - once we got two cows my mother managed - so that we all had our milk all the year round you know, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 People whose cows went dry like that, did they simply do without milk then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Well they would get milk from a neighbour. Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 In exchange for something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Well they - they might have to do the same thing - in reverse again you - see at another occasion. Oh people didn't look for repayment like that, you know. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did you have anything different say on a Sunday for breakfast or was it always porridge every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Ah well, I - I don't - possibly not, possibly there'd be - bacon and egg, there was oh plenty of eggs, we had hens you see and - probably - bacon. Bacon and eggs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did you have a glass of milk as children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh you'd have a drink of milk, aye, or tea was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 You were allowed to drink tea as children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh yes, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Was the main meal of the day at midday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Of course this is a bit difficult, we were at school and we were 
rather far away, we were a mile and quarter, a mile and a half away from the school, so - apart from breakfast - we would have a piece probably at school and - then come back. The main meal would be around tea time. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 What would you have for your main meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Oh well, depend on the season of the year, we would have potatoes, smoked herring, potatoes and meat and - most people you know had sheep of their own, killed them in the season and - then again, good used was made of all - parts of the a
nimal. There would be black puddings, white puddings - the sheep's head broth. And - you had a roast and we had a wee bit of that - one of these old American stoves, my mother would be able to roast things as well. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 That was rather unusual wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Then another thing probably not so common but with the - with the shop being available and - she being used to these she could produce lovely puddings. Dumplings. All kinds of things, yes, a wide variety of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 With fruit in it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Yes, dried fruits, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 That was rather uncommon wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 
Yes, of course there were economic factors you see, people couldn't have - the - standard of living as - pretty poor, that times and very difficult for people to - they wouldn't spend mone
y on anything but - pure essentials. Things like sweet biscuits, jam, things like that you know a lot of people just wouldn't - couldn't afford to buy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Your mother did though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 But - well we had - perhaps we'd have a - we'd probably enjoy a bette
r standard of living than the others, just because - with the shop there was - some money increment and the - fruit was there, so we had - we used to always have it on that account.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 What about making of beer or wines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Ah well no, we - but - I re
member we used to get a thing there but it was in the shop, from here you get them today, a packet and - in a bakers shop down at Stornoway and you could - make what they call tonic stout or - tonic ales and this kind of thing, but - I don't remember that
 
we ever made - beer, there - there was some kind of beers - people made. Certainly some kind of drink where there were a - some - activating agent like yeast. I don't know that it was yeast, probably it was and - you made it up with treacle and water and 
- whatever this - fermenting agent was. And - it's a pleasant drink.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Were you given this as children too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh yes, well it was harmless and very pleasant.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Did you grow your own vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Yes. Oh yes. Oh yes. Once we'd got the croft, 
