e Civil Service, either the National Assistance Board of National Insurance. But - I opted, I should have really - and I could have got quite a good appointment through the National Assistance because we were doing National Assistance work on an agency ba
s
is, in the highlands, Public Assistance Departments were doing this on an agency basis for the - Assistance Board. And the natural thing would be for me to have applied for a post with the Assistance Board and - I would have had - a good opportunity of ha
ving had a - of being in charge of the local office, but - I was a bit diffident about it and I - felt you know, I was - I wasn't terribly sure that - working - just without}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523904\charrsid16660515  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 code by book or rules as you would do in the Civil Service, and being a Lewis man i
nvolved with - lots of - relatives, lots of people you knew, that this was a particularly good idea, and I opted for a lower grading in the - National Insurance set-up. And eventually I got the offer of an appointment as an executive officer there, but - 
I
 - I - at the - same time a full time post became available in the Education Department. I applied for that, then my own post as Public Assistance Officer was going into the melting pot - because the people we'd been giving public assistance to, they were
 
all being taken over by the National Assistance Board you see. So that my own post was being revised. I had the - experience of being offered - three appointments in one week. And - fortunately I made up my mind that - if I was successful in my bid for th
