that around the early part of the century - they had a gamekeeper in Barras who was - must have been quite a lot of parts, and he knew about football, he; knew about drama, he was very musical, he could play bagpipes, he could play a violin - he had a pho
n
ograph, one of these things with the cylinders, and - I know my father got - very friendly with him, he used to - he - he used to sing for him. He - he could - he could record the - on - on cylinders you see and - they used to arrange concerts in the loca
l
 schools. They formed a football team I know my father was in the football team. So that I think there was a tradition grew up in Barras probably earlier than any other part of the rural area - and - I have a recollection of - seeing a football a long lon
g
 time ago and - having to contribute a penny or something to it, and - of course I - I don't think anybody was very much aware of the rules but we played with our football. And by that time the shinty had pretty well died out, I don't remember ever playin
g shinty at school. But shinty was the game in my father's time. Yes.
