\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8863920 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 We'd like to know a bit more about it, how were people invited and that kind of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3561112 JM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5316270\charrsid16660515 Oh yes, well - that was a very tricky business. You had to be invited by the - if the bride and bridegroom
 didn't take the trouble to go round and invite you you know it wasn't regarded as a very sound invitation. People could - could be quite - choosy about this you see and decide whether they would go on not - sending a - a little brother or nephew or a cou
s
in or something like that was you know people were quite - sensitive about this. But - there usually - somebody from the - one side or other or maybe somebody from both represented both the bride or bridegroom went round the houses - inviting people. This
 
was it and - the weddings themselves now - well the war weddings again I think come back to me, my uncle was the minister, and in those days could happen was that the - the procession, the whole crowd - procession would go to the - would march to - and pe
rhaps there's a piper, perhaps there wasn't, they would march down to the manse, usually the weddings were held in the manse. And then they walked back again to the bride's home and there they had their festivities.
